ighbor to the right (`in[i-1]`) are '1'. (Example: `out_any[2]` checks `in[2]` OR `in[1]`).\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ and $in[i-1]$.\n   - For $i=1$ to $99$: `out_any[i] = in[i] | in[i-1]`.\n   - For $i=0$: The neighbor to the right (`in[-1]`) doesn't exist, so `out_any[0] = 0`.\n\n3. **`out_different` Logic:** Each bit `out_different[i]` indicates if `in[i]` is different from its neighbor to the left (`in[i+1]`), wrapping around. (Example: `out_different[98]` checks $in[98] \neq in[99]$).\n   - This means for index $i$, we check $in[i]$ XOR $in[i+1]$.\n   - For $i=0$ to $98$: `out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[i+1]`.\n   - For $i=99$ (wrap-around): The neighbor to the left is $in[0]$. So, `out_different[99] = in[99] ^ in[0]`.\n\n**Implementation Strategy:**\nSince all required operations are purely combinational, we will use `assign` statements for maximal efficiency and clarity.\n\n**Syntax Error Advice:**\n- **Array Indexing:** Be careful with array indexing when defining relationships. For example, `in[i+1]` must be valid. Since $i$ goes up to 99, $i+1$ can reach 100, which is out of bounds for `in[99:0]`. This is why we must explicitly handle the boundary conditions (i=99 for `out_both` and i=0 for `out_any`).\n- **Concatenation vs. Slicing:** The hint warns against reverse slicing (`x[1:2]`). We will use direct indexing or concatenation `{in[i], in[i+1]}` if needed, but direct indexing is simplest here.\n\n**Refining Boundary Conditions for Code:**\n\n*   `out_both[99] = 1'b0;`\n*   `out_any[0] = 1'b0;`\n*   `out_different[i] = in[i] ^ in[(i+1) % 100];` (This modulo operation elegantly handles the wrap-around for `out_different`.)\n\nWe can implement the non-wrapping parts using standard assignments and handle the wrap-around separately or use the modulo trick for all three, while explicitly setting the edge cases where the neighbor doesn't exist (like `out_both[99]` and `out_any[0]`).",
